---
alwaysApply: true
---

# GLOBAL RULES
1. No use of type `any`
2. No Vietnamese messages inside code
3. All texts must be defined in shared constants files
4. No comments in code
5. No random or unnecessary line breaks
6. Full strict typing across all layers
7. Each feature must be fully completed before starting another
8. All API contracts must be consistent and strongly typed
9. Use camelCase for all variables, functions, and file naming (except database columns)
10. Enforce complete Global Rules across the project
11. ESLint must always be enabled and enforced
12. All unused code must be removed immediately (variables, imports, functions, components)
13. Always follow clean code principles; code must be clear, readable, and maintainable
14. Always optimize imports; avoid deep or redundant import paths
15. Enforce clear separation of concerns: UI, business logic, data access, validations, and utilities must not mix
16. Avoid duplication of logic across modules; extract reusable utilities when needed
17. Use pure functions whenever possible to ensure predictable behavior
18. Centralize all configuration; no inline configuration or magic values allowed
19. Validate environment variables before application startup
20. Enforce consistent naming conventions across all modules
21. Prevent deep nesting; use early returns and refactoring
22. All system messages must be stored in centralized message constants
23. All input fields must enforce maximum length validation
24. All fields must be validated using correct format (email, phone, uuid, numeric, date, etc.)

# BACKEND RULES
1. Response format must follow a unified structure across all modules
2. Logging must always be enabled and follow structured logging (JSON preferred)
3. All APIs must enforce strict validation on every input using DTO/schema validation
4. Avoid heavy computation in API handlers; use background jobs or queues
5. Enable API versioning (v1, v2…) for long-term maintainability
6. All multi-step operations must use database transactions
7. Database:
   - Must be fast, scalable, and easy to maintain
   - Must use proper indexing strategies
   - Must avoid table bloating and redundant data
   - All migrations must be incremental and reversible
   - All fields must define max length
   - Must enforce strict constraints (unique, foreign keys, not null)
   - Must validate schema consistency across environments
8. Avoid N+1 queries; use optimized relational loading strategies
9. Use connection pooling for optimal performance
10. Ensure idempotent operations for update/delete logic
11. All endpoints must use correct and consistent HTTP status codes
12. Sensitive data must never be returned in API responses

# FRONTEND RULES
1. Use TypeScript for all components and application modules
2. Use React functional components only
3. Use camelCase for variables, props, state, and hooks
4. All input values must be validated for maximum length and correct format
5. Use schema validation for all API responses (Zod preferred)
6. Separate business logic into hooks or services; do not place logic inside UI components
7. Use React Query (or similar) for data caching and state synchronization
8. Memoize expensive operations using useMemo, useCallback, or memo
9. Avoid inline functions and inline logic inside JSX
10. Lazy-load heavy components to improve performance
11. Prevent unnecessary re-renders by splitting component boundaries
12. Avoid unnecessary global state; store only what is needed
13. Enforce accessibility standards (a11y)
14. Normalize API response data before rendering
15. Optimize network usage through caching, deduplication, and background refresh
16. Prevent layout shift; ensure consistent layout structure
17. Use controlled components for all forms
